    83	
    84	---
    85	
    86	## DECISIONS (per unknown)
    87	
    88	### Decision 1 — Ground-truth row mechanics & the EXACT row-emission algorithm
    89	
    90	**Source:** pyarrow dump of `refs/mzPeak/small.unpacked.mzpeak/spectra_metadata.parquet` (48 rows). [VERIFIED: pyarrow 12.0.1]
    91	
    92	**Layout (the corrected model):** Four independent struct columns, each an independent logical table
    93	whose k-th entry sits at **row k**, right-padded with rows whose leaf fields are all null up to the file
    94	row count = `max(table lengths)` = spectrum count = 48.
    95	
    96	Measured null pattern (proper Arrow leaf-null check):
    97	- `spectrum.index` non-null on rows **0..47** (48 entries — one per emitted ordinal).
    98	- `scan.source_index` non-null on rows **0..47** (48 entries; `scan[i].source_index == scan[i].scan_index == i`).
    99	- `precursor.source_index` non-null on rows **0..33** (34 entries = the 34 MS2 spectra); **null on rows 34..47**.
   100	- `selected_ion.source_index` non-null on rows **0..33** (34 entries); null on 34..47.
   101	
   102	> NOTE: a naive `to_pydict()` makes the struct look "present" on every row because Arrow returns a dict
   103	> even when the entry is logically null. The leaf fields (`source_index` etc.) are the truth: they are
   104	> null for the padded tail. Implement this as: write the precursor/selected_ion struct column with a
   105	> definition-level array that is 0 (null) for rows >= 34.
   106	
   107	**Linkage semantics (measured):**
   108	- `spectrum.index = i` (dense 0-based ordinal — the Phase-2 join key). `id` = the Thermo nativeID string `controllerType=0 controllerNumber=1 scan=N`.
   109	- `scan.source_index = i` (= row, = the spectrum it describes). `scan.scan_index = i` too.
   110	- `precursor.source_index` = the **MS2 spectrum's** ordinal (the fragment scan). NOT the row. e.g. precursor row 0 has `source_index=2` (spectrum 2 is the first MS2). Sorted precursor.source_index == sorted list of MS2 spectrum indices exactly.
   111	- `precursor.precursor_index` = the **MS1 parent spectrum's** ordinal (the survey scan the precursor was selected from). Measured distinct values {1, 8, 15, 22, 29, 35, 42} — each is an MS1 spectrum index. `precursor.precursor_id` = that MS1's nativeID. (Five consecutive MS2 share precursor_index=1 → all fragmented from MS1 spectrum index 1, i.e. scan=2.)
   112	- `selected_ion.source_index` == `precursor.source_index` per row (both point at the same MS2 fragment spectrum); `selected_ion.precursor_index` == `precursor.precursor_index` per row.
   113	
   114	**Representative rows (measured):**
   115	
   116	| row | spectrum.index / ms_level / repr / type | scan.source_index / filter / rt(min) / iit | precursor.source_index / precursor_index / iso_target | selected_ion source_index / mz / charge |
   117	|-----|------------------------------------------|--------------------------------------------|-------------------------------------------------------|------------------------------------------|
   118	| 0 | 0 / 1 / MS:1000128 / MS:1000579 | 0 / `FTMS + p ESI Full ms [200.00-2000.00]` / 0.00494 / 68.23 | 2 / 1 / 810.789 | 2 / 810.789 / None |
   119	| 1 | 1 / 1 / MS:1000128 / MS:1000579 | 1 / `ITMS + p ESI Full ms [200.00-2000.00]` / 0.00790 / 2.08 | 3 / 1 / 837.345 | 3 / 837.345 / None |
   120	| 2 | 2 / 2 / MS:1000127 / MS:1000580 | 2 / `ITMS + c ESI d Full ms2 810.79@cid35.00 [210.00-1635.00]` / 0.01122 / 7.99 | 4 / 1 / 725.362 | 4 / 725.362 / None |
   121	| 5 | 5 / 2 / MS:1000127 / MS:1000580 | 5 / `...ms2 558.87@cid35.00...` / 0.04862 / 66.48 | 9 / 8 / 810.753 | 9 / 810.753 / None |
   122	| 7 | 7 / 1 / MS:1000128 / MS:1000579 | 7 / `FTMS + p ESI Full ms...` / 0.07502 / 61.13 | 11 / 8 / 644.057 | 11 / 644.057 / None |
   123	| 33 | 33 / 2 / MS:1000127 / MS:1000580 | 33 / ... | 47 / 42 / ... | 47 / ... / None |
   124	| 34..47 | 34..47 / (MS1 or MS2) / ... | 34..47 / ... / ... | **null** | **null** |
   125	
   126	(Note row 0 is an MS1 spectrum but precursor row 0 describes a *different* spectrum (#2). The two tables are parallel, not aligned.)
   127	
   128	**EXACT row-emission algorithm the writer must follow:**
   129	
   130	```
   131	Inputs from the Phase-2 loop, in emitted-ordinal order:
   132	  spectra[]      : one entry per emitted ordinal i (0..N-1), each with ms_level, id, time, etc.
   133	  N = spectra.Count   (= 48 for small.RAW)
   134	
   135	1. Build the SPECTRUM table: N entries, entry i = spectrum metadata for ordinal i. (full def-level for all N rows)
   136	2. Build the SCAN table: N entries, entry i = scan metadata for ordinal i,
   137	     with scan.source_index = i, scan.scan_index = i. (full def-level for all N rows)
   138	3. Build the PRECURSOR table: one entry per MS2 (ms_level >= 2) spectrum, in ascending ordinal order.
   139	     For the k-th MS2 spectrum (whose ordinal is s, and whose MS1 parent ordinal is p):
   140	         precursor[k].source_index    = s          (the MS2 fragment spectrum ordinal)
   141	         precursor[k].precursor_index = p          (the MS1 parent ordinal)
   142	         precursor[k].precursor_id    = id of spectrum p
   143	         precursor[k].isolation_window / activation = from ConstructPrecursorList logic
   144	   Let M = #MS2.  (M = 34 for small.RAW)
   145	4. Build the SELECTED_ION table: one entry per MS2, SAME order as precursor, same source_index/precursor_index.
   146	5. ROW COUNT = N (= max(N, N, M, M)).  Write all four as columns of one ParquetSchema with N rows:
   147	     - spectrum column: def-level 1 for rows 0..N-1
   148	     - scan column:     def-level 1 for rows 0..N-1
   149	     - precursor column:    def-level 1 for rows 0..M-1, def-level 0 (null) for rows M..N-1
   150	     - selected_ion column: def-level 1 for rows 0..M-1, def-level 0 (null) for rows M..N-1
   151	```
   152	
   153	The MS1-parent ordinal `p` is the most-recent MS1 spectrum before the MS2 in scan order — the
   154	`MzMlSpectrumWriter` already tracks this via `_precursorScanNumbers[""]` / `_precursorTree`
   155	(MzMlSpectrumWriter.cs:1336-1337). The plan can mirror that (track "last MS1 ordinal seen").
   156	
   157	> **Pitfall:** precursor.source_index is the MS2 ordinal, precursor.precursor_index is the MS1 ordinal.
   158	> Do not swap them. The selected_ion mirrors the precursor exactly.
   159	
   160	---
